comment.text:
This is the bookplate of James Foster Holmden, b. 1919.  The arms of the Holmden family (a family with roots in Edenbridge, Kent, United Kingdom back to the 1500s) are described in Arthur Charles Fox-Davies, "Armorial Families: A Directory of Gentlemen of Coat-Armour," Hurst & Blackett, 1929, Vol 1., p. 963, as follows:
     Sable, a fesse between two chevrons ermine. Mantling sable and argent.
     Crest — Upon a wreath of the colours, an otter's head erased or.
     Mottoes — " Vive ut vivas" ; " Semper viret."

James Foster Holmden was the second son of Frank Alfred Amphlett Holmden, a Major in the British Army during the Boer War who was awarded the Distinguished Service Order, an honor given for gallantry on the battlefield.  According to "Armorial Families," he was born in 1919.  His mother, Elsie Mary Foster, died in 1921 when he was 2 years old.  He followed his father's footsteps into the military, being commissioned a Second Lieutenant in the Royal Regiment of Artillery in 1941 (Appointment published in the Supplement to the London Gazette [Issue 35146] 25 April 1941, page 2431).  What became of him after this, I do not know.

An identical bookplate to the above is also attributed to James Foster Holmden in the Notre Dame University Library Rare Books & Special Collections Bookplate Registry.

Robert Taylour gained the rank of Colonel in the service of the 6th Dragoon Guards. He held the office of Member of Parliament (M.P.) for Kells between 1790 and 1800.

comment.text: Des aubadeurs ioueurs d'instrumens et coureurs de nuyt. [Some serenaders, instrumentalists, and debauched night-owls.] Ex libris: Antony Constans This humorous picture shows an unruly band of serenaders, in the dead of night, playing outside the window of a scantily clad woman, who is showing her appreciation by emptying a chamber pot in their direction. The spelling looks intentionally archaic ("ioueurs" instead of "joueurs"; "nuyt" instead of "nuit"). An "aubade" is a dawn serenade [1]; "coureurs de nuit" was defined in older French dictionaries as folks who stay up all night, and for whom the night is as day [2]. In one reference to the usage of the term in 18th century France [3], the term is described as referring to disorderly bands of youths who would disturb the public peace at night, and was used in conjunction with terms such as "libertins" and "debauches", which seems to accord with the depiction. So, who is this Antony Constans, who festooned his books with a depiction of French libertines? A university professor, apparently. A compilation of faculty scholarship at Birmingham-Southern College from 1918-2007 [4] identifies him as having been on the faculty of that institution from 1928-1954, as a professor of French and Italian. It also provides a short description of his education: B. ès Lettres, Université de Grenoble, 1914; B. ès Droit, Université de Grenoble, 1918; Licencié ès Lettres, Université de Grenoble, 1919; Ph.D., Harvard University, 1926; Certificat de Prononciation, University of Paris, 1935; Diplôme de Phonétique, University of Paris, 1935. Two of these degrees are also listed for Antony Constans in a Harvard catalog of its graduates published in 1930. [5] He also received a Palme académique from the French government in the mid-1930s [4] – a distinction for university professors originally created by Napoleon in 1808 [6]. To this can be added a few additional posts. Antony Constans was described as being an instructor of romance languages on the faculty at the University of Minnesota, in a 3 March 1922 article in the "Minnesota Daily" describing the opening of a play presented by the French club on campus. [7] A 1930 newspaper article in the Huntsville Daily Times describes him as a “former professor at Yale University” [8], indicating perhaps a short appointment there as well. He was apparently well thought of by his academic peers. He was a member of the Executive Committee of the South Atlantic Modern Language Association from 1939-1941, [9] and the South Atlantic Regional Representative of the American Association of Teachers of French from 1941-1943 [10]. Antony Constans is found in the old catalog of the Library of Congress, as a co-editor of book containing an early unpublished play by the French comedic playwright Charles-Simon Favart, entitled “Polichinelle, comte de Paonfier,” [11] which was published in Paris in 1924 [12] and New York in 1932. This publication is also mentioned in the Birmingham-Southern College compilation [4]. Antony Constans died in December 1954 at the age of 57, according to a communication from the archivist at Birmingham-Southern College. They are checking their rare books for a similar bookplate. His age at death would indicate a birth in 1897. His attraction to old French literature and affinity for theater and parody certainly fit with his bookplate. comment.text:
I believe that this is the bookplate of Evelyn Louisa Cecile Eden, who was born circa 1870 and who died on 24 June 1948.

The coat of arms here is of the Eden family of England, associated with the dual titles of Baronet of West Auckland in County Durham and Baronet of Maryland (yes, that would be the State of Maryland).  Among the notable members of the family through history are the former British Prime Minister, Sir Anthony Eden (who served during the 1950s and whose career was ended by the Suez Crisis) and Sir Robert Eden, the last British Governor of the Colony of Maryland.

Sir Robert Eden was named as Governor by the Proprietor of the colony (Frederick Calvert, the last Lord Baltimore) after marrying Caroline Calvert, his sister.  The couple were well regarded in Maryland.  Caroline County in Maryland (erected 1773) is named after her and the county seat was originally to be called Edentown.  Today it is known as Denton, which is explained in some sources as a shortened version of the original name.  Sir Robert returned to Maryland in 1783 after the Revolutionary War, along with an illegitimate son of Frederick Calvert, to see if he could recover some compensation for the former lands of the proprietors.  Sir Robert took ill, died, and was buried in Annapolis.

The copy of Burke's Peerage available to me has a replica of the above seal (not as nicely done, and including a knight's helmet on the crest -- perhaps this element connotes the baronetcy) and a long list of the members of the Eden family from the initial creation of the baronetcy in 1672.  Only one member of the family (including spouses) has the initials "E.L.C." -- Evelyn Louisa Cecile Eden.  She was the eldest daughter of Charles Calvert Eden (1837-1878) and his wife Cecile (d. 1931), who was the daughter of the Freiherr von Sinner of Merchlingen, Switzerland (freiherr is the German equivalent of baron).  Charles and Cecile were married on 16 December 1862.  Burke's and similar references to British nobility seem not to be very interested in the birth dates of daughters, but Evelyn's brother, Morton Frederic Eden, was listed as born on 16 June 1865, so a birth date for Evelyn Louisa Cecile before 1870 is likely.  As one might guess from her father's middle name of Calvert, she was a lineal descendant of Sir Robert Eden -- his great-great-great granddaughter.  Sir Anthony Eden was her second cousin.

It is possible that a British newspaper might have carried her obituary in 1948, and thus a birth date might be available from that source.  Burke's notes that she never married.

Cf.  Burke's Peerage, Baronetage, & Knightage, 102 Ed.  London: Burke's Peerage Limited, 1959, pp. 762 (arms), 764 (E.L.C. Eden).

comment.author: 40252563@N04
comment.text:
I believe this inscription has two parts -- the top part is a little silly poem in Dutch, probably penned by the person who gave the book to Mr. van den Branden, and the bottom is Mr. van den Branden's own "Ex Libris" and signature.  Here is how I would render the text and the translation (with the help of a friend I consulted who knows a little Dutch).  There is probably a misspelling in the third line.

j. franciscus van den branden
verkoopt liedkens alderhanden
en als hij niet [e]indigt zeer fijn
dan zal hij meest bedregen zijn.

J. Franciscus van den Branden
Sells all kinds of little songs
And if one doesn't turn out very fine
Then he will be most disappointed.

It is possible that the initial "J" in the first line is actually a "Ji" (there seems to be a very faint letter "i"), which could be a variant of "Jij" or "you".  That would make the first line directly addressed to van den Branden.  The conjugation of the verb "verkopen" in the second line could be either second- or third-person singular.

comment.text:
Henry Houston Bonnell (1859-1926) was an 1880 Penn graduate (Class Prophet and recipient of the Spoon Award; cf. the Record for his year). After earning his BA, he worked for some years in publishing before retiring to concentrate on literary scholarship and philanthropy. His collection of works by and related to the Brontë family went after his death to the Brontë Parsonage Museum. A. Edward Newton, who advised both Bonnell and his widow to make the bequest, wrote of him:
Many years ago, nearer fifty than forty, I had a friend -- he is dead now -- who, like myself, was a member of a little club which devoted itself to the study of English literature. His name was Henry Houston Bonnell; unlike myself, he was not only pious, but good, really good. When I first knew him he was not rich, but he inherited wealth, and in between the various philanthropic activities to which he devoted his life he became a book-collector and a student of the English novel. He concealed from his friends -- at least from me -- the fact that he wrote hymns. I am glad of this. (Derby Day and Other Adventures (Boston: Little, Brown, 1934), p. 298-299)

"As historian, archivist, and collector, Verreau played a prominent role, especially in the field of Canadian history. His main interest was the early period. To remedy certain deficiencies in the libraries he had visited, he suggested that Canada send them historical works such as the proceedings of historical societies. comment.text:
"Sam'l Bancroft Junr.
"Rockford
"Near Wilmington Delaware"

This is the bookplate of Samuel Bancroft, Jr. (1840-1915), a noted industrialist and philanthropist and huge fan of the Pre-Raphaelites.  Would the book in which this is found by any chance relate to them?

The Delaware Art Museum contains a major manuscript collection of the Pre-Raphaelites that was donated after the death of Samuel Bancroft, Jr.  This short biographical sketch is taken from the Frick Collection directory of American Archives, which includes the Samuel and Mary R. Bancroft Pre-Raphaelite Manuscript Collection (http://research.frick.org/directoryweb/browserecord2.php?-action=browse&-recid=6630):

"Biography Of Samuel and Mary R. Bancroft, Jr.

"The Samuel and Mary R. Bancroft Collection of Pre-Raphaelite art at the Delaware Art Museum in Wilmington, Delaware, is unique. No other art collection is devoted specifically to this important nineteenth century movement, and it is doubtful that there are many other collections so thoroughly documented.

"The collection came about through the personal taste and enthusiasm of Samuel Bancroft Jr. (1840-1915), a Wilmington Quaker industrialist, and his family and business connection with Manchester, England.

"Bancroft was the son of Joseph Bancroft (1803-1874) of Rockford (now part of the city of Wilmington), who emigrated from Lancashire to the U.S.A. in 1824. Joseph was following his brother John, who had emigrated in 1821, and his parents, John and Elizabeth (Wood) Bancroft who, with their other eleven children had emigrated in 1822. John and Elizabeth settled on the Brandywine Creek near Wilmington and John took a partnership in a small flannel mill on a site on the north bank of the Brandywine just west of the present Market Street bridge. That lasted until 1826 when John with Elizabeth and the younger children moved to Providence near what is now Media, Pennsylvania, and there started another woolen textile mill. About the same time, 1826, John the oldest child opened a business as a soap boiler and tallow chandler in Philadelphia, and Joseph moved to Rockland, Delaware, to be superintendent of William Young's cotton mill there. He had served his apprenticeship in Lancashire in an uncle's cotton spinning and weaving mill.

"In 1831, Joseph Bancroft moved to Rockford, 3 miles downstream on the Brandywine, and established his own mill in some buildings which had earlier been used for a grist mill. His development of this mill and his command of good Lancashire practice in spinning and weaving (he returned in 1854 to learn of the latest processes not only in spinning and weaving but in finishing), laid the foundation of the family's wealth. In 1865, Joseph took his two sons, William P. and Samuel Jr. into partnership, the business thereafter being known as Joseph Bancroft and Sons .

"After their father's death in 1874, the brothers became sole owners of the mill, which prospered and expanded in the 1880s, owing mainly to the excellence of the finishing and dyeing processes that Joseph and Samuel had added to the spinning and weaving. In 1889 the brothers incorporated the business, having brought in younger men to undertake the day-to-day management. Samuel, who had been closely involved with the technical development, became president of the company, and it was from this time that he began seriously to collect pictures.

"Bancroft's first major purchase was made in 1890, and was a painting by Dante Gabriel Rossetti (1828-1882) called Water Willow (1871), an important work by arguably the most interesting artist of the movement. Rossetti was a poet as well as an artist and his poetry was an important part of his particular appeal to Bancroft.

"Bancroft was barely a generation younger than the Pre-Raphaelites and was able to meet some of them, their families, dependents, and others who had known them personally, during his frequent visits to England. He was a sympathetic supporter, on occasion, of several who were in financial difficulties. His correspondence with their survivors was preserved with characteristic foresight.

"Although the strength of the collection was established by the end of the century, Bancroft continued to add to it until his death, and the collection eventually comprised over one hundred paintings and drawings, many prints, over two hundred and fifty early photographic reproductions, a valuable literary manuscript collection, a library on Pre-Raphaelite art and the associated literature of the period , and complete records concerning his acquisitions.

"After his death in 1915, Samuel's widow and two children, Joseph and Elizabeth (Mrs. John Bird) decided to keep the collection intact as a memorial to him, and to add to it as the opportunity occurred. It was the only art collection of international quality in the Wilmington area, as Jessie Rockwell (Mrs. Henry Rockwell) the family-appointed first curator of the collection (from 1929-1941) was to point out. Before his death in 1936, Joseph and his sister made arrangements for the gift of the collection, library, and archive, to the Wilmington Society of the Fine Arts (which had already been founded in 1912). The gift included land for a future museum building, and subsequently, an endowment for its maintenance, in memory of both their parents. The museum building was completed in 1938 and the collections moved into it from Samuel Bancroft's house "Rockford," which was soon afterwards demolished."

comment.author: 58880069@N07
comment.text: Interesting woodcut: it seems to be a representation of Augustus (Emperor Octavian) by his birth sign, Capricorn. In ancient astrology, Capricorn is depicted as a goat with a fish's tail (or "Seagoat"), stemming from the myth of Pan, a goat-god attacked by Typhon and driven into the Nile, with its parts above water remaining goat but those under water transformed into fish. Apparently, Augustus was so confident of the greatness of his destiny and the importance of his sign Capricorn, that he published his horoscope, and struck silver coins bearing the image of Capricorn: www.flickr.com/photos/28433765@N07/5297006668/

The bulk of his notable library, some 22000 volumes, was sold in 1790 to Peter Friedrich Ludwig, Duke of Oldenburg (1755-1829) and formed the basis of the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg (founded 1792 and still in existence). Brandes also collected engravings and Michel Huber published a 2-volume catalog of the collection under the title Catalogue raisonné du cabinet d'estampes de feu Monsieur Brandes, secrétaire intime de la Chancellerie royale d'Hannovre (Leipzig: Rost, 1792-1794). These engravings appear to have been sold at auction in 1796. Two separate sales were planned: the first at Easter (18 April), comprising the English, German and Italian items; the second at Michaelmas (3 October), comprising items from France and the Netherlands. Cf. For more information on Brandes's library, including reproductions of his bookplate, see the online exhibition at the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg here, as well as G. comment.text: stamp transcription: "Sigillum Societatis Patrum Sancti Edmundi Pontiniacensis" heading: Society of Saint Edmund images here: www.araldicavaticana.com/zCRC07.htm provenance details: Cf. www.araldicavaticana.com/zcongregazioni_clericali.htm SOCIETA' DI S.EDMONDO Societas Patrum S.Edmundi Oblatorum S.Cordis Iesu et Immacolati Cordis Mariae: S.S.E. (1843) La Congregazione usa oggi una semplice Croce patente di colore rosso con le seguenti lettere poste sul braccio orizzontale: S· S· E Il primo scudo qui rappresentato era in uso negli Stati Uniti fra il 1895 e il 1907 quando la Congregazione era denominata “Oblati del Sacro Cuore di Gesù e dell’Immacolato Cuore di Maria” . Trattasi di “armi parlanti”, di cui daremo qui la spiegazione: Nella parte superiore dello scudo troncato, davanti al simbolo dell’universo, abbiamo sulla destra il Sacro Cuore di Gesù e sulla sinistra quello di Maria. Nella parte inferiore troviamo con qualche variante rappresentato lo stemma dell’Abbazia cistercense di Pontigny in Francia, dove la Congregazione fu fondata dal Padre Muard. La struttura, qui rappresentata con tre archi, rappresenta il ponte che attraversa il fiume Serein nei pressi dell’Abbazia di Pontigny; la parola francese “pont” si combina con la parola “gny” formando “Pont(i)gny”. La parola “nid” suona invece in francese come la parola “gny” in Pontigny. I fiordalisi sono invece il tradizionale simbolo del Regno di Francia. Sotto lo scudo un cartiglio recita il motto: DE CORDE MATRIS AD COR FILII. Nel 1907, per evitare confusione con altre Congregazioni che si richiamavano ai Sacri Cuori, il Capitolo Generale di Parigi cambiò il nome in “Società dei Padri di S. Edmondo di Pontigny” e venne adottato il seguente sigillo ufficiale, ancora oggi in uso. Originariamente era usato fin dal 1905 in Inghilterra, ma la sua origine è a tutt’oggi sconosciuta. Il sigillo, di forma ovale tradizionale riporta la legenda “SIGILLUM SOCIETATIS PATRUM SANCTI EDMUNDI PONTINIACENSIS. Rispetto al primo stemma si notano la sparizione dell’albero con l’uccello nel nido e dei due fiordalisi, tipici di Pontigny. All’interno del sigillo è rappresentato un Religioso della Congregazione mentre formula la professione inginocchiato davanti alla Vergine Maria con l’intercessione del patrono S. Edmondo, in piedi dietro di lui. La cerimonia della professione avviene sopra il ponte da cui la celebre abbazia cistercense di Pontigny prese il nome, ed in questo caso appaiono due campate al posto delle tre dello stemma precedente e dell’unica originaria dell’Abbazia di Pontigny. Nella parte superiore dell’ovale abbiamo una nicchia a tre arcate architettoniche in stile gotico. Sotto l’arco destro un angelo sostiene all’interno di un cerchio il sacro Cuore di Gesù, mentre sotto quello sinistro un altro angelo sostiene il Sacro Cuore Immacolato di Maria. Sotto l’arco centrale, la mano di Dio, è rappresentata porgente una Croce in circolo verso il Religioso inginocchiato, che simboleggia le parole di Nostro Signore: “Chi vuol venire dietro di me, rinunzi a se stesso, prenda la sua croce e mi segua”. self-description: Cf. www.sse.org/ "Founded as a small “missionary band” in 19th century France, The Edmundites have always served where they are needed... "The Society of Saint Edmund is a Catholic order of priests and brothers who share a common life and a profound commitment to improving people’s lives and deepening their relationship with the Church and with God, particularly in communities where the needs are greatest. Our ministry is based upon a service model. We build communities of faith by making ourselves available and present to the people we minister to, as well as those who minister with us. Collaborative, inclusive, hospitable and approachable are a few of the words lay partners, students, parishioners and others frequently use to describe The Edmundites." also relevant: Abbaye de Pontigny en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pontigny_Abbey
